  </p>
</div>
<div class="reportSection size">
  <h4>Size</h4>
  <p class="large">
    This {{#isCollection}}collection{{/isCollection}}{{^isCollection}} area of interest {{/isCollection}} is <strong>{{size}} square kilometers</strong>.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="reportSection tableContainer">
  <h4>Deep Sea </h4>
  <div class="in-report-header">Deep Sea Minerals: <a href="#" data-toggle-node="5450a05b4eb580f13c02c9d3" data-visible="false">show mineral layers
  </a></div>
  <table> 
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th style="width:170px;">Type</th>
        <th>Area (sq. km)</a></th>
        <th>Area (% of total region)</th>
      </tr>
      {{#mining}}
      <tr>
        <td>{{TYPE}}</td>
        <td>{{SIZE_SQKM}}</td>
        <td>{{PERC_TOT}}</td>
      </tr>
      {{/mining}}
    </thead>
  </table>
  <div><a class="details" href="#">show details</a>
    <div class="hidden">
      <div class="list-header">The deep sea resources available for extraction are divided into 4 types:</div>
      <ol>
        <li>Polymetallic Nodules (Manganese, Copper, Nickel, Cobalt) - 4,000 - 6,000 m depth</li>
        <li>Cobalt-rich Manganese Crusts (Cobalt) - 800 - 3,000 m depth</li>
        <li>Sulphide Deposits (Copper) - 1,500 - 4,000 m depth</li>
        <li>Deep-sea mud (rare earth elements, yttrium) - 2,000 -6,000 m depth.</li>                                    
      </ol>
      <p>
          The DSM deposits are higher in mineral content than on-land deposits. Typical value of a tonne of land based ore is 50-200 USD, for sea floor deposits it’s 500-1500 USD. DSM mining in the PACIOCEA  has a strong potential.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

</div>

<div class="reportSection tableContainer">
  <h4>Coastal Fisheries </h4>
      <p class="large">
        The term coastal fishery resource means “any fishery, any species of fish, or any stock of fish that is broadly distributed across the coastal waters (12 nautical miles) under the jurisdiction of a country.
      </p>
      <div class="in-report-header">Coastal Catch: <a href="#" data-toggle-node="5450a05b4eb580f13c02c9e9" data-visible="false">show coastal catch layer</a></div>
      <table data-paging="10">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th colspan="2"></th>
            <th colspan="4">Catch (in tonnes)</th>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th>Country</th>
            <th>% of Total Coastal Catch</th>
            <th>Total</th>
            <th>Demersal </th>
            <th>Pelagic  </th>
            <th>Invertebrate </th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {{#coastal_catch}}
          <tr>
            <td>{{COUNTRY}}</td>
            <td>{{PERC_TOT}}</td>
            <td>{{TOT_TONS}}</td>
            <td>{{DEM_TONS}}</td>
            <td>{{PEL_TONS}}</td>
            <td>{{INV_TONS}}</td>
          </tr>
          {{/coastal_catch}}
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <div><a class="details" href="#">show details</a>
        <div class="hidden">
            <p>
                Within the PACIOCEA region, the highest catch volumes are located in Papua New Guinea, Fiji, Kiribati, Federated States of Micronesia and Solomon Islands. Demersal species dominate the catch (33% to 75%). Demersal fisheries represent an important part of the total catch explained by the presence of lagoons and local fishing techniques
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
    <div class="in-report-header">Coastal commercial catch vs. coastal subsistence catch</br>
      <a href="#" data-toggle-node="5450a05b4eb580f13c02c9eb" data-visible="false">show commercial/subsistence catch layer
      </a>
    </div>
      <table data-paging="10">
        <thead>

          <tr>
            <th>Country</th>
            <th>Commercial Catch (kg per capita)</th>
            <th>Subsistence Catch (kg per capita)</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {{#comm_sub_catch}}
          <tr>
            <td>{{COUNTRY}}</td>
            <td>{{COM_KG_CAP}}</td>
            <td>{{SUB_KG_CAP}}</td>
          </tr>
          {{/comm_sub_catch}}
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <div><a class="details" href="#">show details</a>
        <div class="hidden">
          <p>
              Within the PACIOCEA area, the coastal catch volume is largely dominated by subsistence fisheries. The largest per capita volume of coastal catch (both commercial and subsistence) is located over the smallest land areas. This fact can be related with the low potential of these countries to develop agriculture. Thus, coastal degradation of natural habitats and pollution increase can have repercussions on food security for smaller land area countries.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
</div>

<div class="reportSection tableContainer">
  <h4>Oceanic Fisheries 
    <a href="#" data-toggle-node="5450a05b4eb580f13c02c9e6" data-visible="false">show oceanic catch layers</a>
  </h4>
      <p>
        The term oceanic fishery resource means “any fishery, any species of fish, or any stock of fish that is broadly distributed across the exclusive economical zone (between 12 and 200 nautical miles) under the jurisdiction of a country.
      </p>
      <table data-paging="10">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th colspan="2"></th>
            <th colspan="2">Domestic Catch</th>
            <th colspan="2">Foreign Catch</th>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th>Country</th>
            <th>Total (tonnes)</th>
            <th>tonnes </th>
            <th>% of catch in EEZ</th>
            <th>tonnes</th>
            <th>% of catch in EEZ</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {{#ocean_catch}}
          <tr>
            <td>{{COUNTRY}}</td>
            <td>{{SK_TOT}}</td>
            <td>{{SK_DOM}}</td>
            <td>{{DOM_PERC}}</td>
            <td>{{SK_FRN}}</td>
            <td>{{FRN_PERC}}</td>
          </tr>
          {{/ocean_catch}}
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <div><a class="details" href="#">show details</a>
        <div class="hidden">
          <p>
              Western and Central Pacific offshore fisheries represent more than 60% of total worldwide fisheries and 80% of the Pacific tuna catch. Oceanic fisheries represent 90% of total sea food production in the PACIOCEA area. Foreign fleets dominate Northern oceanic catches. In the south of the PACIOCEA area the domestic catch represents more than 50 % of offshore fisheries. Highest total catch volumes are produced by Papua New Guinea, Kiribati and the Federated States of Micronesia.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
</div>
</div>
