<div class="reportSection tableContainer">
  <h4>Energy</h4>
      <div class="in-report-header">Fuel Imports: &nbsp<a href="#" data-toggle-node="5450a05b4eb580f13c02c9d0" 
        data-visible="false">show fuel import layer</a></div>
        <table>
          <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Country</th>
                <th>% of GDP from Fuel from Imports</th>
              </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {{#fuel_import}}
            <tr>
              <td>{{Country}}</td>
              <td>{{Fuel}}</td>
            </tr>
            {{/fuel_import}}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      <div><a class="details" href="#">show details</a>
        <div class="hidden">
          <p>
            Until this decade, all the countries’ energy supply depended on petroleum and in consequence relied heavily on import. Fuel import can represent from 5% of GDP (Papua New Guinea) to 28% of the GDP (Cook Islands). Changes in the demand, including for the service sector, pose an increasing threat to energy security for Pacific populations.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    <div class="in-report-header">Renewable Energy: &nbsp<a href="#" data-toggle-node="5450a05b4eb580f13c02c9d2" 
      data-visible="false">show renewable energy layer</a></div>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Country</th>
            <th>% of Electricity generated by Renewable Energy</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {{#renewable_energy}}
          <tr>
            <td>{{Country}}</td>
            <td>{{Renew}}</td>
          </tr>
          {{/renewable_energy}}
        </tbody>
      </table>
        <div><a class="details" href="#">show details</a>
        <div class="hidden">
          <p>
            The ocean could produce energy via the implementation of new technologies. Thermal technology and wave energy conversion are estimated the most fruitful potential new resources. Even if these solutions are recent and devices are still expensive, in the long term, they should offer a very competitive alternative to fossil fuel. Moreover, the Pacific could be a key region in the development of some of these solutions by allowing the industry to mature and become competitive. A Framework for Action on Energy Security in the Pacific was established under the guidance of SPC with CROP agencies.
          </p>
        </div>

</div>


